16'00"

What is a switch :

It's a physical device that sits inside a local area network (LAN).
It connects multiple devices within the local area network.
It help these devices talk to each other. It allows simultaneous communication.
It manages where data is sent and receives (it manages traffic, forwarding data to intended
recipient).
A switch can also be connected to a router.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

What is a router :

A router is a physical device, networking device.
It sits between the LAN and the external network (WAN), for example the internet.
It connects the LAN to the WAN.
Router operate at the internet layer of the transmission control protocol or if we referring to
the OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) that would be the network layer.
Routers connect us to the internet and other networks (this is called the Wider Area Network :
WAN).
Routers can have multiple IP addresses for different networks.
It uses routing tables to determine the best path for data to travel and forwards data packets
between the multiple networks.
For example, a mobile phone wants to connect to the internet. It sends a request to the router
then the router connects it to the internet if it approves.


OSI : le modèle OSI est une norme de communication de tous les systèmes informatiques en réseau.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

What is a gateway :

A gateway and a router is often the same device which can be confusing.
The only difference is their function :
	- the router routes data packets between different networks and determines the best path
	for data to travel based on IP addresses,
	- a gateway acts as a gate between two networks, allowing them to communicate. It can
	connect networks that use different communication protocols as well.

A gateway has a single IP address which is of the router that serves as the entry and exit point
for a network.
(Une passerelle possède une seule adresse IP, celle du routeur qui sert de point d'entrée et de
sortie à un réseau.)

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Useful chart :


CIDR (host bits in the 3rd and 4th octets)	/17	/18	/19	/20	/21	/22	/23	/24
CIDR (host bits in the 4th octet)		/25	/26	/27	/28	/29	/30	/31	/32
bits values - network increment			128	64	32	16	8	4	2	1
Subnet mask - decimal value of the host portion	.128	.192	.224	.240	.248	.252	.254	.0

example :
CIDR : /17
Subnet mask : 255.255.128.0
IP ranges : 	x.x.0.1 to x.x.127.254
		x.x.128.1 to x.x.255.254

