Exercises

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Could a router be used as a switch ?  

ChatGPT said:
Yes, a router can often be used as a switch, but only under certain conditions. Here’s how and why this works:

Key Points
Switch Functionality in Routers:

Most modern routers have built-in Ethernet ports designed for connecting multiple devices. These ports act as a simple switch when devices are connected to them.
Traffic between devices on these ports does not need to go through the router's core routing functions, so the devices can communicate as if they were connected to a standalone switch.
Disabling DHCP for Pure Switch Use:

To use a router purely as a switch, the DHCP server on the router needs to be disabled.
When DHCP is disabled, the router will no longer assign IP addresses, and an existing DHCP server (usually on your main router) will handle that task.
Connection Setup:

Connect one of the LAN ports of the router (not the WAN port) to your main network or modem.
Use the other LAN ports to connect your devices. This bypasses the router's NAT (Network Address Translation) and routing functions.
IP Configuration:

Assign a static IP address to the router within the subnet of your main network to avoid conflicts (e.g., if your main router's IP is 192.168.1.1, set this one to 192.168.1.2).
Wireless Access Point (Optional):

If the router has Wi-Fi, it can also serve as a wireless access point while functioning as a switch.
Limitations
Performance: Routers generally have fewer LAN ports compared to dedicated switches, so they may not scale well for large networks.
Advanced Features: Dedicated switches often provide advanced features like VLANs, which most consumer-grade routers do not support.
Configuration Effort: Setting up a router as a switch requires some manual configuration, while a standalone switch works out of the box.
